<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-312-146  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 312 146.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  April 3 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Pentagon loosens export rules for Eastern Europe.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>McMullen, Barbara E.; McMullen, John F.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer industryUnited States. Department of DefenseGovernment RegulationExportEastern Europe.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>PENTAGON LOOSENS EXPORT RULES FOR EASTERN EUROPE WASHINGTON, D.C.,andO;U.S.A.,1990 MAR 30 (NB) - In a move apparently aimed at improving the accessof American businesses to the Eastern European technology market, the DefenseDepartment has relinquished its role as a reviewer of certain types ofcomputers, telecommunications equipment and other technological items thatare now deemed to pose &quot;minimal security risk&quot; if sold to the Soviet Union orthe Eastern European countries.andM;The change in procedure will not eliminate these reviews but will rathertransfer the review responsibility to the Commerce Department, an agency thathas been considered much more liberal in allowing trade with the EasternEuropean nations.andP;  The Pentagon will continue to review licenses for itemssuch as supercomputers that are considered to have higher securityimportance.andP;  The Defense Department will also no longer exercise its right toblock the exhibition of certain high technology items at trade shows inEastern Europe and the Soviet Union.andM;United States firms have long complained that products that United Statesfirms are prohibited from selling to Eastern Europe are readily available tothose nations from other sources such as South Korea.andP;  The lifting ofPentagon review comes at a time when there has been much attention focused onEastern European trade policy.andM;Senator Bill Bradley (D-NJ) said in a published speech, &quot;We must alsofacilitate access to up-to-date technology and equipment.andP;  The U.S.andO;government should take the lead in revamping strategic-trade controls so thatEast European nations can buy the robots, computers and other items they willneed in a modern economy.andP;  This can be done without touching sensitivemilitary issues.&quot;andM;Commerce Secretary Robert A. Mosbacher, who now has the licenseresponsibility for these items, said in a written statement that the move&quot;reflects the Administration's understanding of changing circumstances inEast-West relations.&quot;andM;(Barbara E. McMullen andamp; John F. McMullen/19900331)</TEXT></DOC>